# Mallows Cp from Kunz lecture 3

## Only going to include industry 1 as a proxy since all industries had a similar individual cp score
subdat = df[['annearn', 'married', 'nrtheast', 'nrthcen', 'south', 'male', 'white', 'union', 'office', 'ind1']]
# ^ includes ind1, just cut off

model_ind = smf.ols(formula = 'annearn ~ married + nrtheast + nrthcen + south + male + white + \
    union + office + ind1', data = df)
results_ind = model_ind.fit()
y_mallows = df['annearn']
y_pred = results_ind.fittedvalues

storage_cp = pd.DataFrame(columns = ["Variables", "CP"])
k = 10 # number of parameters in orginal model (includes y-intercept)

for L in range(1, len(subdat.columns[1:]) + 1):
    for subset in itertools.combinations(subdat.columns[1:], L):
        
        # join the strings in the data together
        formula1 = 'annearn~'+'+'.join(subset)
        
        # get the cp
        results = smf.ols(formula=formula1, data = df).fit()
        y_sub = results.fittedvalues
        p = len(subset)+1 # number of parameters in the subset model (includes y-intercept)
        
        cp = mallow.mallow(y_mallows, y_pred,y_sub, k, p)
        
        # add to the dataframe
        storage_cp = storage_cp.append({'Variables': subset, 'CP': cp}, ignore_index = True)

Outliers and Unusual Observations¶

Generally speaking we see outlier observations at $annearn > 80,000$. These observations seem to have unusually high y values that does not follow a related trend in the x values. This is consistent across all variables. There does not seem to be many high leverage points with the exception of perhaps one observation at the far right end of our plots. Additionally, there seems to be one influential observation in our $exper$ variable scatter plot that has both a very high x value and a very high y value.

Non-Linearities¶

Qualitatively there does not seem to be a lot of non-linearities in our quantitative variables. They seem to all generally follow a positive linear trend. $insur$ and $pension$ may exhibit some slight quadratic behavior since $annearn$ seems to decrease at very high values of $insur$ and $pension$. For these variables, it may make sense to include a quadratic term, but we would need to test this explicitly by including higher order terms in our regression and checking their significance.

If we included non-linear variables in the regression model without transformation, then we would get very poor fits to our model. We would be trying to fit a linear relationship on a variable that does not exhibit that behavior. Hence, the standard errors would be very high and the parameter estimates would likely be insignficantly different from 0.

Part 2e. NaN Imputation¶

We have no missing observations so we do not need to do any imputation.

Part 3. Model Building¶

In this section, we will explore several competing Ordinary Least Squares multiple regression models. In particular, our models will contain some combination of quantitative and indicator variables.

In our task to find the best overall model, we will begin with a base model and run it through our framework which consists of several different tests. Through this framework we will get a visual and quantitative assessment of our model and use that to iteratively build a better and better model, Hence, we will only delcare one model at the beginning of this section but will work through many models as we go through our analysis.

Ultimately, we will finalize our model and discuss the economic significance of our parameters and any inferences we can draw from our best model.

Part 3. Model Declaration¶

As stated above, we will now declare our base model using the variables found in part 1 and explored in part 2.

The first model we will consider is:

$$ \begin{align*} annearn_i &= \beta_0 + \beta_1 exper_i + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 annhrs_i + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$
In [6]:
# Base Model
mreg1 = smf.ols(formula = 'annearn ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final).fit()

The estimated model is thus:

$$ \begin{align*} \underset{(se)}{\widehat{annearn}_i} &= \underset{(1783.45)}{-2095.84} + \underset{(26.47)}{104.81} exper_i + \underset{(720.53)}{508.38} married_i + \underset{(755.90)}{3346.35} male_i + \underset{(1058.64)}{1713.15} white_i + \\ &- \underset{(781.39)}{952.65} union_i + \underset{(761.30)}{1772.51} office_i + \underset{(0.72)}{1.93} annhrs_i + \underset{(1.65)}{3.53} vacdays_i + \underset{(1.37)}{2.18} insur_i + \\ &+ \underset{(0.87)}{1.97} pension_i \quad , \quad \textrm{Adj. } R^2 = 0.307 \end{align*} $$

We will now begin testing and working on this model to iteratively improve it and in the process compare it against competiting versions.

Part 3. Multicolinearity¶

Firstly, we consider the case of multicolinearity. Recall from the scatterplot matrix that some of our variables were highly correlated with one another. This suggests that multicolinearity may be a problem. In order to test whether it is an issue, we check our VIFs.

# VIF: Test for multicolinearity

# Extract matices using patsy
y, X = pt.dmatrices('annearn ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final, return_type='dataframe')

# Get VIF
K = X.shape[1]
VIF = np.empty(K)
for i in range(K):
    VIF[i] = smo.variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i)

Part 3. Heteroskedasticity¶

Next, we will examine our model to see if heteroskedasticity is an issue. Recall, if we have heteroskedasticity then one of the core assumptions of OLS will be violated and thus our parameters will not be BLUE.

To do this, we will impelement a Breusch-Pagan Test.

In [9]:
# BP Test for Heteroskedasticity
## H_0: var = constant
name = ["Lagrange multiplier statistic", "p-value", "f-value", "f p-value"]
test = sms.het_breuschpagan(mreg1.resid, mreg1.model.exog)
print("BP Results:")
print(list(zip(name, test)))

BP Results:
[('Lagrange multiplier statistic', 25.293312760132256), ('p-value', 0.004816409140254677), ('f-value', 2.5905334323168376), ('f p-value', 0.004421885080568314)]

From our test, we get a p-value of 0.0048 which is less than 0.05. Because our BP test results in very low p-value, we conclude that variance is not constant and thus heteroskedasticity is an issue we will need to address.

To address this problem, we will first use robust standard errors.

In [8]:
# Robust Standard Errors
mreg1_robust = smf.ols(formula = 'annearn ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final).fit(cov_type = 'HC0')

#print(mreg1_robust.summary())

## pull out squared residuals
df_final_copy = df_final.copy()
df_final_copy["res2"] = mreg1_robust.resid**2

## Try to predict the squared residuals using a linear combination of our variables
mreg1_robus_aux = smf.ols('res2 ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data=df_final_copy).fit()

## Get the regression f-statistic (f-test version)
f = mreg1_robus_aux.fvalue
fp = mreg1_robus_aux.f_pvalue

print("The F-Statistic for the Auxiliary Regression is: "+ str(f) +" and the P-Value is: "+ str(fp))

### We still have heteroskedasticity

The F-Statistic for the Auxiliary Regression is: 2.5905334323168376 and the P-Value is: 0.004421885080568314

Firstly, even with robust standard errors, a BP test (this time using the f-stat verison), still results in a very low p-value (0.0044) which means that our model still has issues of heteroskedasticity even with robust standard errors.

Additionally, robust standard errors seems to generally increase our standard errors to the point where many of our variables are no longer statistically significant.

We will now show our residual plots to get an idea as to which variable(s) might be causing heteroskedasticity within our model. This would allow us to try and use something like Weighted Least Squares or Genearlized Feasible Least Squares to remedy the issue.

From the above plot, it seems that all of our quantitative variables might exhibit some heteroskedastic tendancies; however, $exper$ seems to have the greatest spread of variance with increasing x values. Hence, at least qualitatively, we suspect that $exper$ might be the culprit. However, for completeness's sake, we will implement Feasible Genearlized Least Squares which should serve to correct our issue of heteroskedasticity.

In [9]:
# Generalized Least Squares
df_final_copy["ehatsq"] = mreg1.resid**2

# Estimate Weights
w_est = smf.ols('np.log(ehatsq) ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data=df_final_copy).fit()

vari = np.exp(w_est.fittedvalues) # Estimated Variances
w = list(1/vari)

mreg1_fgls = smf.wls(formula = 'annearn ~ exper + married + male + white + union + office + \
    annhrs + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final_copy, weights = w).fit()

#print(mreg1_fgls.summary())

# Test for Heteroskedasticity
name = ["Lagrange multiplier statistic", "p-value", "f-value", "f p-value"]
test = sms.het_breuschpagan(mreg1_fgls.resid, mreg1_fgls.model.exog)
print("BP Results:")
print(list(zip(name, test)))

BP Results:
[('Lagrange multiplier statistic', 25.082252821919703), ('p-value', 0.005191758394566018), ('f-value', 2.5679991893505107), ('f p-value', 0.004778736421842558)]

Once again, implementing a BP test shows that heteroskedasticity is still an issue. The p-value for this BP test is 0.005 which is below our 5% level.

Thus, neither Robust standard errors nor FGLS were able to mitigate our heteroskedasticity issues. From the above residual plots, I hypothesize that the heteroskedasticity is due to the variable $exper$. I will test this by removing $exper$ from the model and re-testing for heteroskedasticity.

BP Results:
[('Lagrange multiplier statistic', 9.308133517894968), ('p-value', 0.40933069923633003), ('f-value', 1.0330576219948104), ('f p-value', 0.41183428464178373)]
White Results:
[('Lagrange multiplier statistic', 9.308133517894968), ('p-value', 0.40933069923633003), ('f-value', 1.0330576219948104), ('f p-value', 0.41183428464178373)]

Firstly, we conducted a BP test on the model without $exper$ and got a p-value of 0.41 which implies that heteroskedasticity is no longer an issue. However, for the sake of completeness, we will also use a White test to see if heteroskedasticity is an issue. The resulting p-value from this test is also 0.41.

Hence, without $exper$, the model no longer has issues of heteroskedasticity (via both BP and White Test). This means that moving forward we will work with the new model

$$ \begin{align*} annearn_i &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 annhrs_i + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

For now, we will leave our $\beta$ coefficients with their original indicies so as to not cause confusion in cross model comparisons.

Part 3. Model Misspecification¶

Next, we will see if our model is correctly specified at order 1. To do this, we will conduct a Ramsey RESET test with power 2. If our RESET p-value is very low then that implies that our model should have higher order terms.

In [13]:
# Ramsey RESET
RESET = dg.linear_reset(mreg2, power=2, test_type='fitted', use_f = True)

print("Ramsey-RESET:")
print(RESET)

Ramsey-RESET:
<F test: F=2.1129958535731483, p=0.14657166041125327, df_denom=605, df_num=1>

The above Ramsey RESET test results in a p-value of 0.15 which is great than 5%. Hence, we reject the null hypothesis that our model needs higher order terms and we say that our model is correctly specified at degree 1.

Part 3. Evaluating Transformations¶

In this section, we will evaluate transformations to our variables. Notably, we will focus our attention on log transformatinos (log-linear, log-log, linear-log). Our scatterplots from part 2 might not obviously suggest the need for log transformations, but that behavior still seems like it could fit our variables.

We do not consider quadratic terms because RESET test indicated to us that we do not need higher order terms.

Additionally, we will not be applying a Box-Cox or Yeo-johnson transformation since our model is not intended to be a predictive model. It does not really make sense to predict annual earnings based on the variables in our model (vacation days, pension, hours worked, etc.); rather, our model is more useful for determining causality and examining relationships. In that sense, Box-Cox or Yeo-Johnson transformations wuold make our model hard to interpret.

Thus, instead, we will look at log transformations. Notably, we can only apply log transformations to our dependent variable and our independent variable $annhrs$ because all of our other predictors contain observations with 0s (which would break log transformations). Hence, the 4 models we look at are:

The non-transformed model (no $exper$) (M1):

$$ \begin{align*} annearn_i &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 annhrs_i + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

The Log-Linear model (M2):

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 annhrs_i + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

The Log-Log Model (M3):

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

The Linear-Log Model (M4):

$$ \begin{align*} annearn_i &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

Part 3. Interaction Terms¶

Of the variables in our model, the only interactions we suspect makes any economic sense is the combined effect of being a white male on annual earnings and the combined effect of being male and annual hours worked on annual earnings. Interactions between other terms do not appear to make economic sense, thus we will only consider 2 interaction terms:

White x Male:

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \delta_1 (male_i \times white_i) + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

Male x ln(annhrs):

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_2 married_i + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_4 white_i + \\ &+ \beta_5 union_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) + \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \\ &+ \beta_{10} pension_i + \delta_2 (male_i \times \ln(annhrs_i)) + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$
In [20]:
# Testing for Interaction Terms

## White Male
mreg3 = smf.ols(formula = 'np.log(annearn) ~ married + male + white + male:white + union + office + \
    np.log(annhrs) + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final).fit()
#print(mreg3.summary())

## Male annhrs
mreg3_1 = smf.ols(formula = 'np.log(annearn) ~ married + male + white + union + office + \
    np.log(annhrs) + male:np.log(annhrs) + vacdays + insur + pension', data = df_final).fit()
#print(mreg3_1.summary())

For first interaction term model, we get that our $\delta_1$ coefficient has a p-value of 0.1 which makes it insignificantly different from 0. Hence, this interaction term does not fit into our model.

For the second interaction term model, we get that our $\delta_2$ coefficient has a very small p-value and thus is statistically significant; however, its coefficient estimate is negative. This implies that the marginal effect of $\ln(annhrs)$ is:

$$\frac{\partial \ln(annearn)}{\partial \ln(annhrs)} = \beta_7 + \delta_2 male = 1.29 - 0.83 male$$

This implies that being male has a negative effect on the benefit of ln(annhrs) on our independent variable of ln(annearn). This seems to contradict the reasoning for including the interaction to begin with where we might think that men are disproportionately rewarded for extra work. Thus this contradiction leads us to believe that we should not include it in our model.

Thus, we move forward not including any interaction terms in our model. They are either insignificant or lack theoretical sense.

Part 3. Resolving Model Issues¶

Multicollinearity¶

Although our VIF test did not indicate to us that multicollinearity is an issue with our model, we know that a few of our variables are highly correlated. Thus, we will see if the model improves when we drop some of these correlated variables.

Before we do this, we will first drop some variables that are statistically insignificant. Namely, these insignificant variables are the indicators: $married$, $union$, and $white$.

After this, we will drop $pension$ since (recall from the scatterplot from part (2) it has correlations of 0.79 and 0.73 with our other two predictors $vacdays$ and $insur$. We will then evaluate our model with these omissions.

Log-Log Model (reduced variable count) M5:

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) \\ &+ \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

In this sense, we have largely resolved our model's issues with multicolinearity.

Part 3. Bootstrapping¶

In this section, we will test the robustness of our coefficient estiamtes by bootstrapping our model. In other words, we will sample with replacement from our original data and run many regressions and plot histograms showing the distributions of our parameter estimates and adjusted $R^2$ values.

In [248]:
# Bootstrapping
boot_slope1 = []
boot_slope2 = []
boot_slope3 = []
boot_slope4 = []
boot_slope5 = []
boot_interc = []
boot_adjR2 = []
n_boots = 100
n_points = df_finalNO.shape[0]
for i in range(n_boots):
 # sample the rows, same size, with replacement
    sample_df = df_finalNO.sample(n=n_points, replace=True)
 # fit a linear regression
    ols_model_temp = smf.ols(formula = 'np.log(annearn) ~ male + office + \
                              np.log(annhrs) + vacdays + insur', data = sample_df)
    results_temp = ols_model_temp.fit()
 
 # append coefficients
    boot_interc.append(results_temp.params[0])
    boot_slope1.append(results_temp.params[1])
    boot_slope2.append(results_temp.params[2])
    boot_slope3.append(results_temp.params[3])
    boot_slope4.append(results_temp.params[4])
    boot_slope5.append(results_temp.params[5])
    boot_adjR2.append(results_temp.rsquared_adj)

Hence, we generally say that our model holds up well to bootstrapping.

Part 3. Simple Out of Sample Performance and k-Fold Cross-Validation¶

Finally, to properly evaluate model performance, we will be implementing out of sample checks. This involves two similar but different procedures. Firstly, we will split our data into testing and training sets (70-30) and predict on the testing set. We will then record the Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) as our measure of model performance. This naive check will then be compared against k-Fold Cross-Validation. In k-Fold, we essentially do the samething but more robustly by implementing 5 folds to our data. Below is code showing the process of splitting, training, and predicting with our models. The results will then be recorded into a summary table at the bottom.

Firstly, we note the difference between the naive check and k-Fold. The naive check only checks one instance of our data while k-Fold checks several different groupings of our data and thus provides a far more robust estimate. From the values shown, the naive case generally falls within the range of k-Fold RMSE values; however, the naive case fails to properly show the fact that there is indeed a range. Hence, k-Fold is a more robust technique for evaluating model performance.

By looking at the table, we quickly see that our base model is by far the worst performing. This is largely due to the lack of log transformations in the original model. Beyond this, the comparisons between M5 and M3 are much more interesting. Using the naive out of sample check, it appears that M3 actually performs ever so slightly better than M5 (although the values are so close this may be negligble). However, when we look at our 5-fold Cross Validation, we see that they are comparable until we get to the last 2 folds where M5 definitively out performs M3. Using this metric, M5 seems to be our best performing model.

Part 3. Marginal Effects¶

Our model (M5) does not contain any interaction or higher order terms, hence we do not have any relevant marginal effects to discuss.

Part 3. Finalized Model¶

Based upon all of our previous work, we say that M5 is our best model:

$$ \begin{align*} \ln(annearn_i) &= \beta_0 + \beta_3 male_i + \beta_6 office_i + \beta_7 \ln(annhrs_i) \\ &+ \beta_8 vacdays_i + \beta_9 insur_i + \varepsilon_i \end{align*} $$

The core logic behind this decision is that M5 has relatively low AIC/BIC values, a comparatively strong adjusted $R^2$, no heterskedasticity, minimially intrusive outlier observations, good looking fitted value and residual plots, robust bootstrapped estimates, and the lowest 5-fold cross validation RMSE of all tested models.

Additionally, M5 mostly satisfies the standard assumptions of a multiple variable OLS model in that it is linear in its $\beta$ values, its residuals are approximately clustered around 0, it does not exhibit heteroskedasticity, it does not seem to have endogeneity issues, and the predictors (except indicators) take a wide range of values. However, one assumption that we cannot be certain is fully satisfied is the multicolinearity assumption. Yes, our VIFs indicate to us that multicolinearity is not an issue, but there still exists moderate correlation between some of the predictors -- granted they are not perfectly correlated. Furthermore, the model has a Jarcque Bera statistic of 92.69 with probability 0, hence $\varepsilon$ is not normally distributed. This, however, is an optional assumption that does not need to be satisfied for OLS to work.

Therefore, we can reveal out final fitted model:

$$ \begin{align*} \underset{(se)}{\ln(\widehat{annearn}_i)} &= \underset{(0.455)}{2.831} + \underset{(0.031)}{0.289} male_i + \underset{(0.030)}{0.149} office_i + \underset{(0.061)}{0.752} \ln(annhrs_i) \\ &+ \underset{(0.000)}{0.0006} vacdays_i + \underset{(0.000)}{0.0003} insur_i + \varepsilon_i \quad , \quad \textrm{Adj. } R^2 = 0.696 \end{align*} $$

In particular, we interpret the model parameters as such:

  • If our subject is male, we expect ln(annearn) to be 0.289 higher. In practical terms this means that the actual value of annearn will be $\exp(.289) \approx 1.34$ higher. Hence, if our subject is male, we expect annual earnings to increase by 33.5%.

  • If our subject works in an office job, we expect ln(annearn) to be 0.149 higher. In practical terms, this means that the actual value of annearn will be $\exp(.149) \approx 1.16$ higher. Hence, if our subject works in an office job, we expect annual earnings to increasse by 16%.

  • For a 1% increase in annual hours worked, we expect annual earnings to increase by 0.752%.

  • For a \$1 increase in the value of vacation days, we expect annual earnings to increase by 0.06%.

  • For a \$1 increase in the value of employee insurance, we expect annual earnings to increase by 0.03%.

In particular, the interpretation of our model parameters is slightly unusual because our model is a semilogarithmic equation; however, the interpretations are still far more palatable than if our model implemented non-standard transformations.

Additionally, our $\beta_0$ variable is not likely to be interpretable here since our model's dependent variable is logarithmic. This means that we are generally more interested in changes to the model rather than absolute values. In this sense, the y-intercept would not be very helpful. Additionally, it does not really make economic sense for someone to work 0 hours annually and still have positive earnings.

As far as economic insights, this model implies that being male has a strong positive effect on the expected annual earnings of an individual. Obviously, our model does not speak as to the root cause of this difference rather that there is a difference in expected annual earnings. Additionally, but not surprisingly, the model implies that being an office worker is likely to improve your annual earnings over not being an office worker. Furthermore, we can infer that the more an individual works, the more we expect their annual earnings to increase.

It is important to note that we might expect a variable like annual earnings to have a diminishing effect; however, our model does not have the higher order terms necessary to model this effect. We chose to not include higher order terms because the Ramsey RESET test deemed it unnecessary. In the appendix, we will very briefly touch on what a model with quadratic terms could have looked like.

from statsmodels.graphics.regressionplots import plot_ceres_residuals

def ceres_plot(model, data, variable):
    
    # produce plot
    plot_ceres_residuals(model, variable)
    ax = plt.gca()
    
    # don't show plot in notebook
    plt.close()
    
    # Pull datapoints from scatterplot from the statsmodels plot
    line = ax.lines[0]
    X = line.get_xdata()
    Y = line.get_ydata()
    
    # Store the results into format that works with seaborn
    df = pd.DataFrame(np.array([X,Y]).T, columns = [variable, "CERES Resdiduals"])
    plt.figure(figsize = (10, 6))
    
    # plot the results in a way similar to R
    sns.regplot(x = variable, y = "CERES Resdiduals", data =df, lowess = True)
    sns.regplot(x = variable, y = "CERES Resdiduals", data =df)
    
    plt.title("CERES Plot "+variable)

ceres_plot(mreg5, df_finalNO, 'np.log(annhrs)')
ceres_plot(mreg5, df_finalNO, 'vacdays')
ceres_plot(mreg5, df_finalNO, 'insur')

These plots suggest that our model might not be such a great predictor at low values of log(annhrs) or high values of vacdays and insur. We can try to look at higher order terms even though our Ramsey RESET test said they were not necessary.

Higher Order Terms¶

Our CERES plots seem to imply that our model could improve with the inclusion of higher order terms. Hence we will briefly explore this. First, we will add in every quadratic term we can to see how that affects our model.

In [38]:
# Let us define our new model
mreg_kiwi = smf.ols(formula = 'np.log(annearn) ~ male + office + \
    annhrs + I(annhrs**2) + vacdays + I(vacdays**2) + insur + I(insur**2)', data = df_finalNO).fit()
#print(mreg_kiwi.summary()) # a high R^2 and low AIC/BIC.

# Do we need more higher order terms?
RESET_kiwi = dg.linear_reset(mreg_kiwi, power=2, test_type='fitted', use_f = True)
print(RESET_kiwi)

# skeptical of the RESET results... All quantitative variables are now order 2, yet
# the test implies we need more second order terms.

<F test: F=34.0524910011983, p=8.788842035518665e-09, df_denom=599, df_num=1>

When including quadratic terms for every variable (even though $vacdays^2$ is insignificant), we find that the adjusted $R^2$ increases to 0.730 and the AIC/BIC values both decrease. This seems to imply that our model has improved with the addition of these quadratic terms. Although, it is important to note that the coefficients for these quadratic terms are extraordinarily small (essentially 0).

Interestingly, the Ramsey RESET test, in this case, has a p-value of nearly 0 which implies that we need more second order terms. So we can add in the interaction term from earlier in the analysis.

In [39]:
# Perhaps, we try adding interactions and seeing what happens now

mreg_strawberry = smf.ols(formula = 'np.log(annearn) ~ male + office + \
    annhrs + I(annhrs**2) + male:annhrs + vacdays + I(vacdays**2) + insur + I(insur**2)', 
            data = df_finalNO).fit()
#print(mreg_strawberry.summary()) 

RESET_strawberry = dg.linear_reset(mreg_strawberry, power=2, test_type='fitted', use_f = True)
print(RESET_strawberry) # The test still says we need more 2nd order terms...
# There are no other economically sensible interactions to add
# Perhaps we cannot put as much value into the RESET test

<F test: F=22.58028958560054, p=2.526889009863131e-06, df_denom=598, df_num=1>

The inclusion of the interaction term does not affect our model performance very much and it, itself, is not very impactful (just like before). However, upon running the Ramsey RESET test again, we still get a significantly small p-value which implies we need even more second order terms. This is a curious puzzle becauae we have included all of the economically sensible second order terms that we can. This casts some doubt on how important one should consider the RESET test to be.
